{{Shrine | name = Kinpō Shrine | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = [[File:Kinpou Shrine, Nikaho.jpg|260px|Kinpō Shrine]] {{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=13|frame-align=center|frame-width=250}} | location = {{ill|Akita Prefecture|ja|秋田県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akita Prefecture|qq=}}, {{ill|Nikaho City|ja|にかほ市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nikaho City|qq=}}, Kisakata Town, Kotaki Aza Nasozawa 1 | coordinates = {{Coord|39|10|55|N|139|56|32|E|scale:10000_region:JP-05_type:landmark|display=inline,title|name=Kinpō Shrine}} | Deities = {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|スクナビコナ|1=Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|qq=}} and eight other deities | Rank = | Established = {{ill|Jōwa 3|ja|斉衡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōwa 3|qq=}} (856) | Main Hall = | Other names = | festival = Second Saturday in June | Rituals = Kotaki's Chōkura-iro Dance | Map = {{location map|Japan Akita|lat_deg=39|lat_min=10|lat_sec=55|lon_deg=139|lon_min=56|lon_sec=32|label=Kinpō Shrine|position=center|width=200|float=center}} }}
'''Kinpō Shrine''' (金峰神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Nikaho City|ja|にかほ市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nikaho City|qq=}}, {{ill|Akita Prefecture|ja|秋田県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akita Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan.
== Deities == * The main deity is {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|スクナビコナ|1=Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|qq=}}, along with eight other deities. ** Before the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}}, {{ill|Ōmonoimi no Kami|ja|大物忌神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmonoimi no Kami|qq=}} (Chōkai Daigongen) and {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaō Gongen|qq=}} were also enshrined.
== History == According to shrine tradition, the shrine was established by {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役小角|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/En no Gyōja|qq=}} as a site to enshrine both Sukunabikona and {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaō Gongen|qq=}}.<ref name="akitajiten">『秋田大百科事典』秋田魁新報編、1981st year ISBN 4870200074</ref> In {{ill|Jōwa 3|ja|斉衡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōwa 3|qq=}} (856), {{ill|Ennin|ja|円仁|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ennin|qq=}} (Jikaku Daishi) subdued the giant "Tenaga Ashinaga" of {{ill|Mount Chōkai|ja|鳥海山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Chōkai|qq=}} and enshrined the deities Chōkai Daigongen and Zaō Gongen. The shrine may have served as a {{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bettō-ji|qq=}} for {{ill|Chōkaisan Ōmonoimi Shrine|ja|鳥海山大物忌神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōkaisan Ōmonoimi Shrine|qq=}}.
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the shrine was known as "Zaō-dō" and associated with the {{ill|Ryūzan-ji|ja|龍山寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryūzan-ji|qq=}} temple. It formed a {{ill|Miyadera|ja|宮寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyadera|qq=}} system and was a central hub of {{ill|Chōkai Shugendō|ja|鳥海修験|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōkai Shugendō|qq=}}, attracting many devotees.
In {{ill|Meiji 2|ja|明治2nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji 2|qq=}} (1869), the shrine was renamed "Chōkai Shrine." By {{ill|Taishō 2|ja|大正2nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō 2|qq=}} (1913), it was further renamed "Kinpō Shrine," incorporating the Kumano Shinmei Shrine on its grounds.
== Rituals == The shrine's annual festival features the "Chōkura-iro Dance," which was designated a National {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} in {{ill|2004|ja|平成16年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2004|qq=}}.
== Cultural Properties == === Akita Prefectural Designated Tangible Cultural Properties === * A pair of wooden {{ill|Komainu|ja|狛犬|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Komainu|qq=}} (designated April 2, 1970) * A standing wooden statue of {{ill|Kannon Bosatsu|ja|観音菩薩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kannon Bosatsu|qq=}} (designated January 9, 1971) – A single-piece carving of {{ill|Japanese cedar|ja|杉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese cedar|qq=}}, possibly from the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}. * Three standing wooden statues of {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaō Gongen|qq=}} (designated January 9, 1971)
== Transportation == * By Rail: {{ill|JR|ja|東日本旅客鉄道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR|qq=}} {{ill|Uetsu Main Line|ja|羽越本線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uetsu Main Line|qq=}}, alight at {{ill|Kisakata Station|ja|象潟駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kisakata Station|qq=}}, take a Yokoka-bound bus for 15 minutes, and disembark at Naso Falls.
