{{Shrine | name = Kinpō Shrine | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = [[File:Kinpou Shrine, Nikaho.jpg|260px|Kinpō Shrine]] {{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=13|frame-align=center|frame-width=250}} | location = [[:en:Akita Prefecture|Akita Prefecture]], [[:en:Nikaho, Akita|Nikaho City]], Kisakata Town, Kotaki Aza Nasozawa 1 | coordinates = {{Coord|39|10|55|N|139|56|32|E|scale:10000_region:JP-05_type:landmark|display=inline,title|name=Kinpō Shrine}} | Deities = [[:en:Sukunabikona|Sukunabikona]] and eight other deities | Rank = | Established = [[:en:Saikō|Jōwa 3]] (856) | Main Hall = | Other names = | festival = Second Saturday in June | Rituals = Kotaki's Chōkura-iro Dance | Map = {{location map|Japan Akita|lat_deg=39|lat_min=10|lat_sec=55|lon_deg=139|lon_min=56|lon_sec=32|label=Kinpō Shrine|position=center|width=200|float=center}} }}
'''Kinpō Shrine''' (金峰神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Nikaho, Akita|Nikaho City]], [[:en:Akita Prefecture|Akita Prefecture]], Japan.
== Deities == * The main deity is [[:en:Sukunabikona|Sukunabikona]], along with eight other deities. ** Before the [[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Shinbutsu bunri]], {{ill|Ōmonoimi no Kami|ja|大物忌神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmonoimi no Kami|qq=}} (Chōkai Daigongen) and {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaō Gongen|qq=}} were also enshrined.
== History == According to shrine tradition, the shrine was established by [[:en:En no Gyōja|En no Gyōja]] as a site to enshrine both Sukunabikona and {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaō Gongen|qq=}}.<ref name="akitajiten">『秋田大百科事典』秋田魁新報編、1981st year ISBN 4870200074</ref> In [[:en:Saikō|Jōwa 3]] (856), [[:en:Ennin|Ennin]] (Jikaku Daishi) subdued the giant "Tenaga Ashinaga" of [[:en:Mount Chōkai|Mount Chōkai]] and enshrined the deities Chōkai Daigongen and Zaō Gongen. The shrine may have served as a {{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bettō-ji|qq=}} for [[:en:Chōkaisan Ōmonoimi Shrine|Chōkaisan Ōmonoimi Shrine]].
During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the shrine was known as "Zaō-dō" and associated with the [[:en:Longshan Temple|Ryūzan-ji]] temple. It formed a {{ill|Miyadera|ja|宮寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyadera|qq=}} system and was a central hub of {{ill|Chōkai Shugendō|ja|鳥海修験|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōkai Shugendō|qq=}}, attracting many devotees.
In {{ill|Meiji 2|ja|明治2年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji 2|qq=}} (1869), the shrine was renamed "Chōkai Shrine." By {{ill|Taishō 2|ja|大正2年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō 2|qq=}} (1913), it was further renamed "Kinpō Shrine," incorporating the Kumano Shinmei Shrine on its grounds.
== Rituals == The shrine's annual festival features the "Chōkura-iro Dance," which was designated a National {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} in {{ill|2004|ja|平成16年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2004|qq=}}.
== Cultural Properties == === Akita Prefectural Designated Tangible Cultural Properties === * A pair of wooden [[:en:Komainu|Komainu]] (designated April 2, 1970) * A standing wooden statue of [[:en:Avalokiteśvara|Kannon Bosatsu]] (designated January 9, 1971) – A single-piece carving of {{ill|Japanese cedar|ja|杉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese cedar|qq=}}, possibly from the late [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]]. * Three standing wooden statues of {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaō Gongen|qq=}} (designated January 9, 1971)
== Transportation == * By Rail: [[:en:East Japan Railway Company|JR]] [[:en:Uetsu Main Line|Uetsu Main Line]], alight at [[:en:Kisakata Station|Kisakata Station]], take a Yokoka-bound bus for 15 minutes, and disembark at Naso Falls.
